#. Tag: title
#: glossary.docbook:2
#, no-c-format
msgid "Glossary"
msgstr "Glosario"

#. Tag: para
#: glossary.docbook:4
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"In this chapter you will find an explanation of most of the <quote>uncommon</"
"quote> words that are used in the handbook."
msgstr ""
"Neste capítulo atopará unha explicación da maioría das palabras "
"<quote>especializadas</quote> que se usan no manual."

#. Tag: glossterm
#: glossary.docbook:8
#, no-c-format
msgid "degrees"
msgstr "graos"

# well-spelled: direccion
#. Tag: para
#: glossary.docbook:9
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Degrees are units to measure angles or turns. A full turn is 360 degrees, a "
"half turn 180 degrees and a quarter turn 90 degrees. The commands "
"<userinput>turnleft</userinput>, <userinput>turnright</userinput> and "
"<userinput>direction</userinput> need an input in degrees."
msgstr ""
"Os graos son unidades para medir ángulos ou xiros. Unha circunferencia "
"completa ten 360 graos, media circunferencia 180 graos e un cuarto de "
"circunferencia 90 graos. As ordes <userinput>xiraEsquerda</userinput>, "
"<userinput>xiraDereita</userinput> e <userinput>direccion</userinput> "
"precisan que dun parámetro expresado en graos."

#. Tag: glossterm
#: glossary.docbook:13
#, no-c-format
msgid "input and output of commands"
msgstr "entrada e saída das ordes"

#. Tag: para
#: glossary.docbook:14
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Some commands take input, some commands give output, some commands take "
"input <emphasis>and</emphasis> give output and some commands neither take "
"input nor give output."
msgstr ""
"Algunhas ordes requiren de entradas (parámetros), outros xeran saídas "
"(resultados), outros toman entradas <emphasis>e</emphasis> dan saídas e "
"outros nin requiren de parámetros nin xeran resultados."

#. Tag: para
#: glossary.docbook:15
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Some examples of commands that only take input are: <screen>\n"
"forward 50\n"
"pencolor 255,0,0\n"
"print \"Hello!\"\n"
"</screen> The <userinput>forward</userinput> command takes <userinput>50</"
"userinput> as input. <userinput>forward</userinput> needs this input to know "
"how many <glossterm linkend=\"pixels\">pixels</glossterm> it should go "
"forward. <userinput>pencolor</userinput> takes a color as input and "
"<userinput>print</userinput> takes a string (a piece of text) as input. "
"Please note that the input can also be a container. The next example "
"illustrates this:"
msgstr ""
"Exemplos de ordes que só toman parámetros: <screen>\n"
"avanza 50\n"
"corLapis 255,0,0\n"
"escribe \"Ola\"\n"
"</screen> A orde <userinput>avanza</userinput> toma o parámetro "
"<userinput>50</userinput>. <userinput>avanza</userinput> precisa deste "
"parámetro para saber cantos <glossterm linkend=\"pixels\">píxeles</"
"glossterm> debe avanzar. <userinput>corLapis</userinput> toma unha cor como "
"parámetro e <userinput>escribe</userinput> un texto. Lembre que os "
"parámetros tamén poden ser variábeis. O seguinte exemplo ilustra isto:"

#. Tag: screen
#: glossary.docbook:18
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"$x = 50\n"
"print $x\n"
"forward 50\n"
"$str = \"hello!\"\n"
"print $str"
msgstr ""
"$x = 50\n"
"imprime $x\n"
"avanza 50\n"
"$str = \"hello!\"\n"
"imprime $str"

#. Tag: para
#: glossary.docbook:20
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Now some examples of commands that give output: <screen>\n"
"$x = ask \"Please type something and press OK... thanks!\"\n"
"$r = random 1,100\n"
"</screen> The <userinput>ask</userinput> command takes a string as input, "
"and outputs the number or string that is entered. As you can see, the output "
"of <userinput>ask</userinput> is stored in the container <userinput>x</"
"userinput>. The <userinput>random</userinput> command also gives output. In "
"this case it outputs a number between 1 and 100. The output of the random is "
"again stored in a container, named <userinput>r</userinput>. Note that the "
"containers <userinput>x</userinput> and <userinput>r</userinput> are not "
"used in the example code above."
msgstr ""
"Exemplos de ordes que xeran saídas: <screen>\n"
"$x = pregunta \"Escriba algo e prema Aceptar… grazas!\"\n"
"$r = aleatorio 1,100\n"
"</screen> A orde <userinput>pregunta</userinput> toma unha cadea como "
"entrada, e devolve o número ou cadea que se insire. Como pode ver, o "
"resultado de <userinput>pregunta</userinput> é gardado na variábel "
"<userinput>x</userinput>. A orde <userinput>aleatorio</userinput> tamén xera "
"saídas. Neste caso devolve un número entre 1 e 100. A saída de aleatorio é "
"gardada tamén neste caso nunha variábel chamada <userinput>r</userinput>. "
"Lembre que as variábeis <userinput>x</userinput> e <userinput>r</userinput> "
"non se usan no exemplo de arriba."

#. Tag: para
#: glossary.docbook:24
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"There are also commands that neither need input nor give output. Here are "
"some examples:"
msgstr ""
"Tamén hai ordes que nin precisan de parámetros nin devolven resultados. "
"Estes son algúns exemplos:"

# skip-rule: proposta-en-clear
#. Tag: screen
#: glossary.docbook:25
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"clear\n"
"penup"
msgstr ""
"borrar\n"
"subeLapis"

#. Tag: glossterm
#: glossary.docbook:30
#, no-c-format
msgid "intuitive highlighting"
msgstr "realzado intuitivo"

#. Tag: para
#: glossary.docbook:31
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"This is a feature of &kturtle; that makes coding even easier. With intuitive "
"highlighting the code that you write gets a color that indicates what type "
"of code it is. In the next list you will find the different types of code "
"and the color they get in <link linkend=\"the-editor\">the editor</link>."
msgstr ""
"Esta é unha funcionalidade de &kturtle; que simplifica aínda máis o escribir "
"os programas. Co realzado intuitivo o código que escribe é colorido cunha "
"cor que indica o tipo de código que é. Na seguinte lista atopará os "
"distintos tipos de código xunto coa cor que teñen no <link linkend=\"the-"
"editor\">editor</link>."

#. Tag: title
#: glossary.docbook:33
#, no-c-format
msgid "Different types of code and their highlight color"
msgstr "Os distintos tipos de código e a cor coa que se realzan"

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:37
#, no-c-format
msgid "regular commands"
msgstr "ordes normais"

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:38
#, no-c-format
msgid "dark blue"
msgstr "azul escuro"

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:39
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The regular commands are described <link linkend=\"commands\">here</link>."
msgstr "As ordes normais descríbense <link linkend=\"commands\">aquí</link>."

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:42
#, no-c-format
msgid "execution controlling commands"
msgstr "ordes que controlan a execución"

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:43
#, no-c-format
msgid "black (bold)"
msgstr "negro (grosa)"

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:44
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"These special commands control execution, read more on them <link linkend="
"\"controlling-execution\">here</link>."
msgstr ""
"As ordes de control do fluxo da execución, lea máis sobre eles <link linkend="
"\"controlling-execution\">aquí</link>."

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:47
#, no-c-format
msgid "comments"
msgstr "comentarios"

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:48 glossary.docbook:83
#, no-c-format
msgid "gray"
msgstr "gris"

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:49
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Lines that are commented start with a comment characters (#). These lines "
"are ignored when the code is executed. Comments allow the programmer to "
"explain a bit about his code or can be used to temporarily prevent a certain "
"piece of code from executing."
msgstr ""
"As liñas comentadas comezan polo carácter #. Estas liñas son ignoradas cando "
"se executa o código. Os comentarios permítenlle ao programados dar "
"explicacións do código e tamén serven para evitar temporalmente que se "
"execute un cacho de código."

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:52
#, no-c-format
msgid "brackets {, }"
msgstr "chaves {, }"

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:53
#, no-c-format
msgid "dark green (bold)"
msgstr "verde escuro (grosa)"

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:54
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Brackets are used to group portions of code. Brackets are often used "
"together with <link linkend=\"controlling-execution\">execution controllers</"
"link>."
msgstr ""
"As chaves úsanse para agrupar porcións de código. As chaves adoitan usarse "
"xunto cos <link linkend=\"controlling-execution\">controladores de "
"execución</link>."

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:57
#, no-c-format
msgid "the <link linkend=\"learn\">learn</link> command"
msgstr "a orde <link linkend=\"learn\">define</link>"

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:58
#, no-c-format
msgid "light green (bold)"
msgstr "verde claro (grosa)"

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:59
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <link linkend=\"learn\">learn</link> command is used to create new "
"commands."
msgstr ""
"A orde <link linkend=\"learn\">define</link> úsase para crear ordes novas."

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:62
#, no-c-format
msgid "strings"
msgstr "textos"

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:63 glossary.docbook:125
#, no-c-format
msgid "<entry>red</entry>"
msgstr "<entry>vermello</entry>"

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:64
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Not much to say about (text) strings either, except that they always start "
"and end with the double quotes (\")."
msgstr ""
"Tampouco hai moito que dicir sobre as cadeas (de texto), só que sempre deben "
"ir entre comiñas (\")."

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:67
#, no-c-format
msgid "numbers"
msgstr "números"

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:68 glossary.docbook:73 glossary.docbook:126
#, no-c-format
msgid "dark red"
msgstr "roxo"

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:69
#, no-c-format
msgid "Numbers, well not much to say about them."
msgstr "Non hai moito que explicar sobre os números."

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:72
#, no-c-format
msgid "boolean values"
msgstr "valores lóxicos"

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:74
#, no-c-format
msgid "There are exactly two boolean values, namely: true and false."
msgstr "Hai exactamente dous valores lóxicos, que son: certo e falso."

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:77
#, no-c-format
msgid "variables"
msgstr "variábeis"

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:78
#, no-c-format
msgid "purple"
msgstr "morado"

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:79
#, no-c-format
msgid "Start with a '$' and can contain numbers, strings or boolean values."
msgstr "Comezan cun «$» e poden conter números, textos ou valores lóxicos."

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:82
#, no-c-format
msgid "mathematical operators"
msgstr "operacións matemáticas"

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:84
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"These are the mathematical operators: <userinput>+</userinput>, <userinput>-"
"</userinput>, <userinput>*</userinput>, <userinput>/</userinput> and "
"<userinput>^</userinput>."
msgstr ""
"Estas son as operacións matemáticas: <userinput>+</userinput>, <userinput>─</"
"userinput>, <userinput>*</userinput>, <userinput>/</userinput> e "
"<userinput>^</userinput>."

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:87
#, no-c-format
msgid "comparison operators"
msgstr "operacións de comparación"

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:88
#, no-c-format
msgid "light blue (bold)"
msgstr "azul claro (grosa)"

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:89
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"These are the comparison operators: <userinput>==</userinput>, <userinput>!"
"=</userinput>, <userinput>&lt;</userinput>, <userinput>&gt;</userinput>, "
"<userinput>&lt;=</userinput> and <userinput>&gt;=</userinput>."
msgstr ""
"Estas son as operacións de comparación: <userinput>==</userinput>, "
"<userinput>!=</userinput>, <userinput>&lt;</userinput>, <userinput>&gt;</"
"userinput>, <userinput>&lt;=</userinput> e <userinput>&gt;=</userinput>."

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:92
#, no-c-format
msgid "boolean operators"
msgstr "operacións lóxicas"

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:93
#, no-c-format
msgid "pink (bold)"
msgstr "rosa (grosa)"

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:94
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"These are the boolean operators: <userinput>and</userinput>, <userinput>or</"
"userinput> and <userinput>not</userinput>."
msgstr ""
"Estas son os operadores booleanos: <userinput>e</userinput>, <userinput>ou</"
"userinput> e <userinput>non</userinput>."

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:97
#, no-c-format
msgid "regular text"
msgstr "texto normal"

#. Tag: entry
#: glossary.docbook:98 glossary.docbook:123
#, no-c-format
msgid "black"
msgstr "negro"

#. Tag: glossterm
#: glossary.docbook:108
#, no-c-format
msgid "pixels"
msgstr "píxeles"

#. Tag: para
#: glossary.docbook:109
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"A pixel is a dot on the screen. If you look very close you will see that the "
"screen of your monitor uses pixels. All images on the screen are built with "
"these pixels. A pixel is the smallest thing that can be drawn on the screen."
msgstr ""
"Un píxel é un punto na pantalla. Se mira moi de preto á pantalla do monitor "
"verá que usa píxeles. Todas as imaxes na pantalla están feitas con píxeles. "
"Un píxel é a cousa máis pequena que pode debuxarse na pantalla."

# well-spelled: vaix, vaiy, tamañolenzo, ancholapis
#. Tag: para
#: glossary.docbook:110
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"A lot of commands need a number of pixels as input. These commands are: "
"<userinput>forward</userinput>, <userinput>backward</userinput>, "
"<userinput>go</userinput>, <userinput>gox</userinput>, <userinput>goy</"
"userinput>, <userinput>canvassize</userinput> and <userinput>penwidth</"
"userinput>."
msgstr ""
"Moitas ordes precisan que se lles pase como parámetro un número de píxeles. "
"Estas ordes son: <userinput>avanza</userinput>, <userinput>retrocede</"
"userinput>, <userinput>vai</userinput>, <userinput>vaix</userinput>, "
"<userinput>vaiy</userinput>, <userinput>tamañolenzo</userinput> e "
"<userinput>ancholapis</userinput>."

# skip-rule: proposta-contracción-de
#. Tag: para
#: glossary.docbook:111
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"In early versions of &kturtle; the canvas was essentially a raster image, "
"yet for recent versions the canvas is a vector drawing. This means that the "
"canvas can be zoomed in and out, therefore a pixel does not necessarily have "
"to translate to one dot on the screen."
msgstr ""
"Nas primeiras versións de &kturtle; o lenzo era esencialmente unha imaxe "
"raster, pero nas máis recentes é un debuxo vectorial. Isto significa que "
"pode achegalo e afastalo, polo que un pixel non se corresponde "
"necesariamente cun punto da pantalla."

#. Tag: glossterm
#: glossary.docbook:116
#, no-c-format
msgid "RGB combinations (color codes)"
msgstr "Combinacións RGB (códigos de cor)"

#. Tag: para
#: glossary.docbook:117
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"RGB combinations are used to describe colors. The <quote>R</quote> stand for "
"<quote>red</quote>, the <quote>G</quote> stands for <quote>green</quote> and "
"the <quote>B</quote> stands for <quote>blue</quote>. An example of an RGB "
"combination is <userinput>255,0,0</userinput>: the first value (<quote>red</"
"quote>) is 255 and the others are 0, so this represents a bright shade of "
"red. Each value of an RGB combination has to be in the range 0 to 255. Here "
"a small list of some often used colors:"
msgstr ""
"As combinacións RGB úsanse para describir cores. O <quote>R</quote> provén "
"de <quote>vermello</quote>, o <quote>G</quote> de <quote>verde</quote> e o "
"<quote>B</quote> de <quote>azul</quote>. Un exemplo de combinación RGB é "
"<userinput>255,0,0</userinput>: o primeiro valor (<quote>vermello</quote>) é "
"de 255 e os outros son 0, polo que isto represente un vermello. Os valores "
"das combinacións RGB deben estar no intervalo de 0 a 255. A continuación "
"amósase unha lista con algunhas cores que se usan a miúdo:"

